`crates/steno/src/expand/infinite/emit/` produces the two C++ header outputs consumed by javelin-ext: the runtime dictionary data (`data.rs`) and a golden-test fixture (`test.rs`) that pins that dictionary's behavior to the Rust reference walker. Depending on this subtree gets you two independent `String`-producing entry points, `emit_data_header` and `emit_test_header`, both fallible via `ExpandError`.

The shared coupling is the stroke encoding: `stroke_mask()` in `mod.rs` defines the 32-bit `StenoStroke` bit layout (bit 0 `#`, banks for left/mid/right keys) and is the single point of truth both `data.rs` and `test.rs` call into. Change the bit layout or key orders and both headers — and their consumer in javelin-ext — must move together. `test.rs` additionally depends on `sample.rs` (sequence generation) and the walker in the parent module; changing what sequences `sample.rs` produces changes what the golden test checks, not what the data header contains, so these two outputs can drift in coverage without breaking compilation.

`sample.rs` exists solely to feed `test.rs`; it has no role in `data.rs`. `data.rs` emits real dictionary rows (types, constructs, backing arrays); `test.rs` emits only fixture data, never consulted by a live lookup, so it may safely embed full expected-text strings without compromising anti-cheat properties that (implicitly) constrain `data.rs`'s row contents. `mod.rs` is pure shared plumbing (stroke encoding, C-string escaping) with no header-emission logic of its own.

No intent.md is present, so no divergence check is possible.